author: James Buchanan
text:
Couple things to consider: 1) Artemis is going to put boots on the ground. C3 is one heck of an accomplishment, but comparing it to Artemis is serious false equivalency. 2) Building anything in the US is far more expensive, simply on a measure of economics. American labor is hella expensive next to literally anyone else on Earth, costs to build are extreme due to the limited amount of competition among established American rocket builders (Lockheed, Northrup Grumman, and Boeing), which leads to competitive bids that are insanely inflated. Just looking at the operational costs of SpaceX's new vehicles shines a damning light on the big three's hugely bloated budgets for orbital class vehicles.

India's program doesn't humiliate NASA's, India's achievements are fantastic, but they're still decades behind NASA's best accomplishments. They exist in a significantly different economic paradigm that makes 1 to 1 comparisons futile.

author: mytube082007
text: Why do we look at ISRO's success as humiliating anyone?  That's very childish of those who do that.  They are two different organizations, supported by very different societies, with very different cost of living, with very different constraints and goals.  ISRO's accomplishments are phenomenal but the science conducted by ISRO and NASA are vastly different.  Thus far, ISRO's objectives have been to perfect the launch, guidance, orbital precision and such technologies.  Science has taken a back seat until now.  As India's economy improves, basic science research will pick up and ISRO too will start doing more science, on top of the launch technology.  At that time, ISRO's mission cost will go up but it will never be the same as NASA because of reasons listed above.  The cost differential is no indicator of how one is more advanced than the other on any aspect.

author: Tech ŒµœÜŒµœÖœÅŒ≠œÑŒ∑œÇ
text:
Great Achievement for sure.

Nevertheless, you can't compare the two. It has more to do with how other companies make the bill for the two of them.

Let's say you are a professional gardener. You charge price based on how much the other house can afford to pay + labour.
So if you work at a big house, you charge them more cuz you know they can afford it and will pay without questions asked.
Smaller house will be charged less + labour. They won't pay if it's not affordable. And definitely won't give you any future work if too expansive.

The same thing happens here. Contractors charge more to NASA cuz it's a big fat cash cow. And they won't charge the same price to the Indian space agency. why? cuz there are just a handful of customers on the whole planet. So why lose them to other competitors.

It's true that ISRO did make some amazing work with budgeting and nobody can beat them on that. But they are also helped by economic differences and how they are seen by the companies that manufacture space-related products.


Before some Indian tries to bash me for whatever reason, just so you know, the same thing happens within the USA itself. Companies make a different bill for the same product to the pentagon and NASA: https://www.youtube.com/shorts/7uvIJBegJ2M

text: Just want to add that the parts were carried on cycle, not because they couldn't afford better vehicles. It was because, the place of the launch was not accessible by roads and the terrain was such that only bullock carts and cycles could safely and slowly carry the equipment. Dr. Sarabhai and his team did not want to disrupt the ecosystem of the village by cutting trees and building roads. But, they could have if they wanted to. Pandit Nehru had given them his full support both by policy as well as through funds. He would have built Dr Sarabhai a road, if he had asked for it.

author: s n
text:
Spiritual Knowledge - Concepts of Science‚Ä¶ (Excerpt from message of Shri Datta Swami)

Science is the logical analysis of the items existing in this creation based on only one authority that is perception (Pratyaksha Pramanam). Even in the ancient logic, all the authorities (Pramanas) are based on perception only. You see the fire giving smoke. This is deduction or perception. When you see the smoke coming from a distance and do not see the fire, you say that fire exists there and this is induction or inference (Anumana Pramanam). But this induction is based on your previous deduction only. Somebody says to you that fire gives smoke. If that person is your dearest, you believe it and infer the fire from the smoke. This is authority of word ‚ÄòShabdha Pramanam‚Äô.

Though you have not seen the fire, your dearest person has seen the smoke coming from fire. Like this all the authorities are based on perception only. I do not find any scripture of any Religion, which contradicts the experience of perception. There are four ways of authority. 1) Sruthi, which is the original scripture. 2) Smrithi, which is the commentaries of Scholars on the original scripture. 3) Yukthi, the logical analysis based on deduction, induction etc., 4) Anubhava, the experience based on the perception of the items in this world, which may be direct or indirect. Out of these four ways, the fourth way is the most powerful. If anything contradicts the fourth way, that is not valid or it may be a misinterpretation based on misunderstanding of the Sruthi or Smrithi or Yukthi. Thus Science and Philosophy are not separate. The very frame of the spiritual knowledge is Science only. Thus Science is the basic foundation and over all underlying structure of all the Scriptures.

A true Scientist should always stand on the perception and should not deny the experience derived by perception. If he denies, he is not a scientist. All top most scientists were philosophers and spiritual people only. Those scientists have travelled along the river of Science and reached its end, which is the ocean of spiritual knowledge called as philosophy. Philosophy is pervading all the branches of Science. Every branch of Science gives Ph.D as the final degree. Ph.D means Doctor in Philosophy. If Science and Philosophy are different, why this word Philosophy is regarded so much by all the branches of Science? Philosophy means the essence of the knowledge of every branch that is experienced when one reaches the end of that branch.

Therefore, the spiritual knowledge, which is the ocean, is the Philosophy in which all branches of Science and all the Religions merge and loose their identity. A scientist who has not reached the end of Science and who is still traveling in the river only denies the existence of the ocean, since he is still perceiving the limiting boundaries of his knowledge ‚Äì river. Such river-travelers are called as atheists.

YouTube Channel: Shri Datta Swami

author: F1 Lap by Lap
text:
India's space program, under the aegis of the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO), doesn't necessarily "humiliate" NASA's budget. Instead, it's been notable for achieving impressive feats with a budget significantly smaller than NASA's.

ISRO has earned a reputation for cost-efficiency, best illustrated by the Mars Orbiter Mission (MOM), also called Mangalyaan. Launched in 2013, this mission successfully inserted a spacecraft into Mars orbit for a total cost of approximately $74 million USD, significantly lower than comparable missions by other countries. For comparison, NASA's MAVEN Mars orbiter, launched in the same year, cost about $671 million USD.

This efficiency comes from various factors such as a lean organizational structure, lower labor costs, and a focus on simpler designs and technology. ISRO's approach often involves doing more with less, innovating with constraints, and gradually building capability over time, which often contrasts with NASA's more high-risk, high-reward strategy that aims for groundbreaking discoveries and advancements in space technology.

It's important to note, however, that comparing ISRO and NASA directly isn't entirely fair or accurate. NASA has a broader and more ambitious range of objectives, including much more extensive scientific research, human spaceflight, and ambitious exploration missions to Mars, asteroids, and beyond. NASA's larger budget supports these goals, as well as the broader American aerospace industry and scientific community.

In conclusion, rather than "humiliating" NASA's budget, ISRO demonstrates a different approach to space exploration, one characterized by remarkable cost-effectiveness. It is an example of how countries with smaller budgets can still make significant contributions to space exploration. The achievements of ISRO do not diminish those of NASA, and vice versa; both are valuable contributors to global knowledge and exploration of space.

author: Era Of Stupidity
text:
It's not quite fair to compare ISRO to NASA. We respect our ISRO and what it has achieved with such a limited budget as our country doesn't have a lot of money to be put aside for RnD.
But NASA has achieved things that are ahead of all the other space agencies put together. The voyager twins are sending data back from distances that are just unimaginable. Then there are two rovers sitting and an aerial vehicle flying on fucking Mars. There's the Parker Solar Probe poking the sun. And not to forget that they are the only agency to put humans on moon, and more importantly got them back unharmed.

The Russian (USSR) space agency was the only other one to actually invest so much on space exploration. China is gaining up some momentum too. But most of their launches are product based ,i.e. they serve a military or private purpose. Space exploration is not their top priority. While NASA has been at the forefront of space exploration. Yes US wastes a lot of money on contractors in defence and space programs, but hey RnD isn't cheap to begin with.
To put it out simply, Stop bashing NASA for a few views you imbecile. Coming from an Indian btw.

author: Arijit Sengupta
text:
You are named Logically Answered - but evidence suggests otherwise! You are comparing what to what? Just by taking finance as the only yardstick you not just fail to justify the idiotic heading for this video, but you also demonstrate the strange need to shout that you are the big kahuna! Have you ever wondered where the "money" is spent? Mission objectives and levels of sophistication are the same is it? And using the word "humiliate" - what gives? NASA sent Man to the moon in 1969, and we are humiliating them isn't it?

ISRO has done well on limited budgets. That is a fact. But to somehow spin that as being greater than NASA is not just being economical with the truth, but downright stuffing facts. Our total national budget (2022) is less than half the research budget of the US. Not to mention that the best minds (including the best Indian minds) work at/for NASA. NASA's remit and ISRO's remit is quite different. And you seem to fail to understand that basic fact. NASA is at the cutting edge of technology, while ISRO is trying build a base from which in maybe a 100 years from now, we will be where NASA is today.

If you really want to showcase ISRO achievements, it would be great if you can stick to facts (other than money) that highlight potential and mission objectives on a budget rather than carp about non existent competition to somehow come across as superior. Just my two bits!

text:
I certainly appreciate India's efforts and applaud their accomplishments. NASA has far more programs and is working on targets such as Luna and Mars. As well as keeping its obligations to the ISS, and all its current assets. India has also benefited from the experience that other space programs have pioneered. So much more cost-effective.
-

In fact, we should not even look at it that way. We should praise India's achievements in conjunction with Nasa's. author: Benjamin Benjamin
text: India's ISRO is getting great in space and I wish them all success  but there are some significant differences that you guys need to see before declaring the low cost missions of ISRO with NASA. ISRO missions are no doubt successful but they are short of complex technologies and let me prove to you guys how. ISRO mission to mars was successful well before China would launch her MARS mission but you need to see the significant differences between the two . China mission to MARS called Tianwen-1 is more complex and have more complex technologies than Indian MARS mission. For example in addition to MARS orbiter like ISRO has on MARS, Chinese Tianwen-1 mission has  Orbiter, Lander and Rover also , A feat that only NASA could accomplish well before China. Similarly NASA missions are well advanced than China and India as NASA is now collaborating with private space contractors like Space X, Boeing , Airbus , ESA , South Korea and New Zealand's Rocket Lab. So every time when people compare the space missions of India with China , India with USA , they forget that it is NOT only the cost that matters as complexity of the missions is also a factor which is significant enought to consider. Lastly, Take an example of NASA APOLLO missions to Moon, China and Russia could only capture a couple of Kilograms of mass from the Moon and could not send crewed missions to Moon until now  but on the other hand NASA placed crews , lander and vehicles on the moon and NASA's Astronauts drove those vehicles on the lunar surface , also collected hundreds of kilograms of mass from the lunar surface which is a huge accomplishment. So all those people who compare NASA space missions with other space missions around the World , they need to understand that NASA is more than 50 years ahead in space when compared to any other Country on the planet earth in space technology and I don't see in our lifetime we would see any Country could approach those milestones and wonders that NASA achieved over the years.  Similarly , If I could explain you the complexity of NASA's HUBBLE and NASA's JWST then it would need more than a couple of pages just to explain the science and technologies that HUBBLE and JWST have on board .

author: joseph jones
text:
I cant speak to india, but Federal contracting regulations tie Nasa‚Äôs hands on cost.
Most parts need to be built stateside by licensed capable contractors. Local machine shops that work on nasa products cant work in other industries due to their insurance company‚Äôs policy. So they cant take on routine work to pay the bills while waiting on new contracts with nasa which increases the overhead they have to pass to nasa.
Its a web of bureaucracy that consumes nasa‚Äôs budget which is forever being restricted by congress.
On top of that, the simulation and testing of each part raises the cost per part to extreme levels. Which is more of a they dont want to be responsible for loss of life, something other countries cough russia cough arent nearly as concerned with and therefore have much better price per launch.
Not to mention the cost of labor in india even for advanced technical work like with aerospace is going to be pennies to the dollar for similar work in the US

author: SerialSnowmanKiller
text:
I think NASA's glory came to an end when their intended re-usable large-scale transport, the Space Shuttle, ended up costing something like twenty times more per launch than it was supposed to. Any competent organization whose goal was to enable the exploration and exploitation of space would have recognized the Space Shuttle as a failure and immediately begun the development of its replacement. Instead, NASA built a handful of Space Shuttles and then... just kept using them, for decades. When the shuttle fleet began to diminish due to accidents, they STILL didn't start development on the next generation, or even build more shuttles to cover the gap. Instead, they just let the shuttle run down its lifespan until they were forced to retire it, and hand off responsibility for getting U.S. machines and men into space to RUSSIA; without even a PLAN to rectify the situation.

I will always be grateful to NASA for what they did in the past, but their time is done.

author: Just Anoman
text:
ISRO have lower mission success rate than NASA and even space X. Not by much, but a concept called diminishing return makes it so that it is exponentially more expensive to get a slight improve in margin once you get pass a certain point, and they are most certainly in that realm.
The PSLV rocket have a 94% success rate, whereas both NASA and space X are at around 98%. Chances are, you can cut launch cost in half if you let the standard "slip" to 94%, which is still higher but much less. On the other hand, getting to 100%, from 98%, would probably cost 10 times more at a minimal, because you would have to build in an unreasonable amount of redundancies and fail safes to approach it(like 99.999%, or 5 9s).
Now, for manned mission, we should go for as high success rate as possible within... some degree of reason. The question is, is it worth it to spend much much more to get a slight higher success rate on instrument launches? I don't think there is a "right" answer for this.

author: Sarmeet Singh
text:
OK. i have to add something to it. I am an Indian but this video is a bit out of context . Reason why Nasa is expensive is because it always is expensive to be the first. They were the first in almost everything minus the first few instances in which the soviets beat them. NASA establishes the science. They collect a list of challenges that they face. Other nations, Including India, we look at them and see the issues they are facing. And we circumvent them. ISRO and NASA are not the same things. There are a lots of list of things handed to them by previous NASA's experiments that they did not have to 'fail and lose money on launch to discover'.
Not saying ISRO's achievements are easy, they have their own set of big challenges and we all as humans and humanity in general should be / are proud of them for what they have managed to achieve. But when we see ILLOGICAL videos on a LOGICALLY answered channel, I guess we really need to put stuff in perspective. Who is first. Who looks at that person's mistakes and lessons and then reaches there afterwards.
It was relatively easier to climb the Mount Everest when it was concurred once and a path to follow footsteps of pioneers was laid out.

author: Advait Unnithan
text: Something I'd like to point out is, it's really not a good way to compare cost efficiency using the cost per kilogram values. The thing with rockets is that the heavier your payload is, the more fuel you need to lift it up, which adds more weight to the rocket (the weight of the fuel), which means even more fuel to lift the rocket, which then adds more weight and this goes on until there is a lot more fuel, which drives up the cost a lot. This means, a heavier payload means that more fuel per kilogram is needed for the launch, which means heavier payload = higher cost per kilogram. There's nothing someone can do about it really. NASA's cost is so high because they are launching much bigger payloads compared to India.

author: retnemmoc101
text:
The framing of this video is pure clickbait BS to pander to Indians.

For a channel called "logically answered", this video completely fails to answer the title's question of "how" ISRO manages with a smaller budget, so I'll give one possible explaination: labour costs.

The median annual income in India is $3k. In the US it's $43k. That's a factor of just over 12 . Any sane person would expect a large difference in raw costs just from labour alone. There's no adjustment for this or any other economic factors in the video.

There isn't even an attempt to explain how, if any cost savings are being made.

NASA no longer recieves massive amounts of funding because there is no longer a need to compete with the USSR, so there is political pressure to reduce funding. Meanwhile, a new drive for exploration and politically expediency in estabilshing India as a new space-faring power is leading to increasing funding for ISRO.

Indians should be proud of the ISRO's impressive accomplishments as it is- there is no need for flawed economic comparison with NASA.

author: Almantas Jurkus
text: Cost effectiveness is not a comparison of like for like. Material cost can be compared that way, but staff costs are significantly different not due to efficiency but due to other factors like local economy and currency values. Scaling for capacity is also very significant. Granted - lack of resources tends to put pressure on ways to make them last longer, but SpaceX has already gained out of inefficiencies of NASA,  so how does ISRO compare against that? It's warped statistics measuring up to old yardstick. If there wasn't so much emphasis on efficiency, it's an encouraging story on how space capacity development is not just about fat wallet.

author: testingbruin
text: As someone who works in the U.S. aerospace industry for a while now and has dealt with program management, you can't simply compare budgets like this. If you account for cost of living and take home salaries in India vs U.S., the weighted budgets differences are a lot less drastic. Of course, not to downplay what they are able to achieve, which is still amazing regardless. And the U.S. Space Program has a lot of requirements that adds to the cost (some that are bureaucratic in nature while others are done in excess and inefficiently obviously). It also takes a lot more resources to develop technology at the forefront versus already seeing it done and building on top of existing lessons learned.

author: Davout
text:
There is a lot of misinformation not to say a bigger word in this video.

First NASA is not a manufacturer. Boeing, Lockheed Martin and SpaceX are manufacturers. One reason why NASA is not all that efficient is the constant changes in leadership of the country. Another reason is companies like Boeing which more and more show they lack efficiency. If the manufacturer lacks efficiency the who operation becomes stagnant and more expensive. Yet that doesn't necessarily means that NASA is inefficient. After all the most efficient entity in the field is SpaceX and SpaceX is what it is largely because of NASA. They saved SpaceX in the very beginning and remained one of the biggest investors in the company in the early to mid period of the SpaceX's development. Furthermore they remain huge for SpaceX to this day. Falcon 9 was developed with NASA's money and now it is the most efficient and the most cost-effective rocket in the world. So don't compare NASA to ISRO in that way. NASA is spending their money everywhere and they obviously have a winning strategy because America + all of the space expiration entities are winning the space race and no ISRO no CNSA can catch them at the moment.

Another misinformation was about the big missions of ISRO. For example the finding water on the moon was not done by India but by NASA. It was launched on Indian rocket but the probe was American.

Now I understand you might have a lot of Indian followers but misinformation is not good for anybody.

I think a major portion of NASA's cost have to do with the cost of labour , so yes of course India will be able to win when it comes to being cost effective. In fact, globally, the cost of labour probably ranks high on costs an organisation has to bear, and while ISRo might have alot of personnel and they might be decent/well paid in Indian standards, their salary is a fraction of what NASA spends on it's personnal. Let's say an average ISRO scientists is paid $15k and the average NASA employee around $70k. Again, look at the ratio of costs, it's quite huge a difference. Plus contracts to companies building components will also be affected.

Everything else that ISRO has achieved though is something it deserves but one thing I can't accept as it's accomplishment is this raw comparision of costs.

author: Navnit Chakrabarti
text:
The only one reason why India's budget is low, because it knows it doesn't have money, and it strives to pull of big things with limited resource

Even NASA can do it on budget, but they have more budget then that of ISRO. Hence it ends up using all the money

( If you have a budget in mind, you can fit essential and cut short not - that - essential things. And you can execute projects economically.

But if you pocket is deep, and you don't have a budget plan, you will end up spending excess money.)

That's all to it

Both the organisation are doing their best. And I hope they make space travel for public economically before I die.

author: Dinkle Berg
text: Comparing NASA's SLS to ISRO's GSLV... You do realize NASA's rocket is supposed to take cargo and humans to the moon right? Not to low earth orbit like what ISRO is trying to do? I do agree that ISRO is doing good, and I also do hate NASA for other shortcomings. But not like this. In order to lift more pounds you gotta add more than just a bunch of fuel. Bigger payload = bigger price per Kg. You need extra thrusters, more sturdier alloys, and more crafty engineering. The GSLV Mark III can carry 30 tons (27216 Kg), compared to the SLS 70 tons (63503 Kg). GSLV, a medium lift launch vehicle meant for low earth orbit. SLS, a super heavy-lift launch vehicle meant to go to the moon. I dislike NASA, but deceiving the public isn't my thing.

Ok. Good job. But going to the moon, sun and planets, will that helps millions of Indian living in slums? Will it help India with proper roadways all thru out the country? Will it help the people with the increasing demand of hospital? Will it reduces petroleum price? Will it give more employment to the millions of unemployed youth? Will it solved the water and air pollution in India? Will it help built more school and provide proper education to millions of children who once become adult easily manipulated by politician for vote bank only?
So why spent millions of rupees, the people's money on something that the Indian mass will not benefit?
Being the first to the moon, planet etc may bring good name to India. But is good name filling your stomach from hunger? Is good name filling the hospital with more bed? Is good name educating the uneducated?

India, and the world government is giving priority to the wrong causes. Once you realised that all this things are useless, it will be too late.

author: Christophe Blanchi
text:
NASA is directed by Congress and congress is highly political. It is not a question of humiliation, it is just that the levels of incomes between the US and India are drastically different resulting in much higher costs.
Conservatives and the GOP in congress could not care less about space unless it is to compete with the Chinese or Russia and show off the US's technological prowess. The GOP is actively against funding projects to measure anything having to do climate change for instance. This is no way to run a space program and NASA is an example of an amazing resource that is being destroyed by the attitude of party over country that the GOP and conservatives have demonstrated time and time again over the last 30 years.
Labor is very expensive in the US and the EU and are a huge component of the space programs. For equal technologies, the west can only compete by bringing innovation.

author: Johnny Thunder
text: SLS isn't gonna cost that much, it's gonna cost ~$850M and it can take 93 Ton to LEO... so roughly = $9140/kg to Orbit... But here's the thing, SLS isn't aimed at LEO, it's aimed at the Moon and can take 45 Tons to TLI, nothing else, not even Starship can do that. ISRO can send ~3.5 Tons to TLI for ~$51M, comparing the two here: 45 Tons / 3.5 tons = 12.88 x $51M = $655.86M, ~20% cheaper however you can't build a manned space program when you can only send ~3.5 Tons to TLI, you need something like SLS to send something big like Orion that can actually keep humans alive for 2 weeks out to the Moon. Would you expect and aircraft carrier to cost more to operate then a tug boat? Of Course!
